 M http://src.chromium.org/viewvc/chrome/trunk/src/native_client/src/shared/platform/win/nacl_secure_random.c?r1=4421&amp;r2=4420&amp;pathrev=4421

name service initial implementation, plus secure random number service
initial implementation.

Also refactored the secure command channel service to use a generic
NaClSimpleServer base class, shared with the name service.

The newly exposed secure random number generator is cryptographically
secure, in the sense that, assuming it is seeded properly (and we
should be), it should generate output that is indistinguishable from
truly random unless the underlying cryptographic primitive (AES) can
be broken.  The generator is not, however, forward secure (a TODO
item), so if an adversary gains access to the computer after a
legitimate user's session and dumps memory contents, then the
adversary is able to reconstruct the generator's output in the
previous browser session.  Closing the browser obviously suffices,
modulo any unscrubbed memory pages that the underlying host OS might
have left behind.

TEST= run_nameservice_test
